args: Dammit... Why isn't this working?\nWhy won't they just acknowledge me?!
Who goes there?! By royal decree,\nnobody is supposed to be here rightâ€”
So you recognize me like this, do you?
There are portraits of you in the castle...\nI've gazed upon the painting of your\ncoronation more times than I can count.
You... But how? I declared that painting an\nexercise in vanity and had it taken down.

That's right. I spent countless hours in
the storeroom where it was locked away.
I'd look at it over and over, wondering if I
would someday end up like you...
...You know what? No! You won't\ndeceive me! My father is long dead!
Yes, you're right. He is dead. But a part of\nhim has been unable to move on, and so\nhe stands before you now.
Think of this as a final admonition from\nyour father, and listen well.
Emile. What happened to this city?

Your tyranny has ravaged the city; your
people grieve. I hear that a significant
portion of the populace has fled the
capital entirely.
Before having a statue built in your\nlikeness, shouldn't you consider fulfilling\nyour responsibilities as a ruler?!
Nnngh... Even you, father? Even YOU \nwould throw that in my face?!

It's always the same! My ï¼‚responsibilities
as a ruler,ï¼‚ my ï¼‚role as a member of the
royal family...ï¼‚ Always that! You think I
don't know? I'd take care of it all if I could!

Do you have any idea what it feels like?
To always be assailed with the exploits of
my elder brothers? To be reminded how
my elder sister would act in my position?
Can you even grasp the MISERY of\nrealizing that I will never, EVER fill\ntheir outrageously oversized shoes?!
You need not imitate your siblings. You\nhave only but to do what you yourself can\ndoâ€”

I DID! And it wasn't enough! A thousand
voices screaming at me that I'm not good
enough as royalty, that I won't be able to
adequately rule if I don't change!
And that's why I decided to say to hell with\nit allâ€”a ruler's responsibilities, all of it!
Even though Father...Father alone told\nme I was enough!

You told me if being a prince was a
burden, I should cast it away. You told me
if I had no need of my duty, I should be rid
of it.
(I did...? I don't rememberâ€”ah.\nHe means the Aurelius of this world.)
And so now you come before me after all\nthis time, and you tell me to do my duty?!
(To think Aurelius said such a thing to\nEmile...)

(Now that I think of it, I never spoke to any
of my children about anything other than
being a ruler and their royal status. Did I
ever speak to them as parent to child...?)
(Even as I was aware of Emile's worries, I\nthought them inevitable, so long as he was\nborn a member of the royal family.)
(The Aurelius in this world was different.\nHe tried to treat his children more\npreciously than I did.)
(Perhaps he valued the love between\nfather and childâ€”a love that I did not\nattempt to experience.)
...I knew it. I've never been anything but an\naggravation to you. A piece of refuse not\nworth sullying your hands with.

What you said to me back then was just
a throwaway commentâ€”just something
perfunctory to get me out of your way
for the moment.
(I am left with but one way to help him\nnow.)
It was wrong of me to try and force you to\ntake on the duties of a ruler if you chose\nnot to take them on of your own accord.
I have never believed you to be inferior.\nIf anything, there were times I thought\nyou well-suited to being a king.
I do not. To begin with, Alberia overrelies\non militarism. Our problem-solving\nmethodology is too biased towards power.
Be it Leonidas or Chelle, they excel at\ndemonstrating their power to make their\nopponents yield.
Consequently, they fail to so much as\nconsider alternative solutions. And this\ncould breed conflict within the kingdom.
In that respect, since a young age, you\nhave had a strong interest in peaceful\npastimes, like painting, song, and dance.
You possessed undeniable ability. I was\nmost impressed with the play you wrote\nabout King Alberius.
Oh, yes. I thought you might be a king\nof literature, one able to change our\nmilitaristic nation.
That you did not walk that path was my\nown fault. Forgive me, Emile.
That's...you've not...\nYou need not apologize, Father...
No. I made too much of those who\nexcelled in political and military affairs.\nIn so doing, I implied their supremacy.
That is why you felt obliged to follow in\ntheir footsteps, and when you could not,\nyou began to abase yourself.
All of it, my own fault.
But remember well this message. Right\nnow, you are guilty of the same sins as I.
The people are forced to take on duties\nthey cannot bearâ€”duties from which there\nis no escape. So what are they to do?

You ought to know better than any the
bitterness of such a fate. Thus do I urge
you to cease imposing your will upon your
people like this. Do you understand?
I can no longer take back my crimes; this\nis precisely why I do not wish for you to\nrepeat them in turn.
That is all I would say. Consider it my\nlast request, and do not forget it.
Wait, Father! Where are you going?!\nCan you not remain here and guide me?
I told you, I have already passed on.\nAnd the dead cannot remain in this\nworld indefinitely.
You have many reliable people who would\nstand at your side. Listen well to their\nopinions, and have them aid you.
Farewell to you, my son. I pray that\nyou become a good and just ruler.
